{"add":{"doc":{"id":"6a6a62c10d1c539a609d66262f72cb8731c9c48db6461e15686083259ce9859c","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Cardiff_English_diphthongs_chart.svg/220px-Cardiff_English_diphthongs_chart.svg.png","previous":[""],"after":["","Aside from lexical borrowings from Welsh like bach (little, wee), eisteddfod, nain and taid (grandmother and grandfather respectively), there exist distinctive grammatical conventions in vernacular Welsh English. Examples of this include the use by some speakers of the tag question isn't it? regardless of the form of the preceding statement and the placement of the subject and the verb after the predicate for emphasis, e.g. Fed up, I am or Running on Friday, he is.[14]"]}}}